From a young age, Jodi-Ann was drawn to the arts, particularly dance and theater. She attended the Edna Manley College for the Performing Arts in Kingston, where she studied drama and theater arts.

After completing her studies, Jodi-Ann moved to the United States to pursue a career in acting. She landed her first role in a Broadway production of "The Lion King," where she played the role of Nala. This role marked the beginning of her successful acting career.

Over the years, Jodi-Ann has appeared in numerous stage productions, including "The Color Purple," "Hairspray," and "The Wiz." She has also starred in several films and television shows, such as "The Game," "Being Mary Jane," and "Power." In addition to her acting work, Jodi-Ann is also a singer and songwriter, and has released her own album, "The Journey."

Outside of her acting career, Jodi-Ann is an advocate for social justice and works with various organizations to promote equality and diversity in the arts. She is also a mentor and role model for young people, particularly those interested in the arts.

Throughout her career, Jodi-Ann has received numerous awards and accolades for her work in the arts. She continues to be a influential and inspiring figure in the entertainment industry.
